Direct Known Subclasses:
JsWin
public class JsWindow
extends DOM.Window.Prototype
implements EventTarget

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.Window class.

The JsWindow object represents a browser window or frame.

In client-side JavaScript, the JsWindow object serves as the global object, and all expressions are evaluated in the context of the current JsWindow object. This means that no special syntax is required to refer to the current window, and you can use the properties of that window object as if they were global variables. Similarly, you can use the methods of the current window object as if they were functions. In addition, the JsWindow object also implements all the global properties and functions defined by core JavaScript.

Js.win() returns the current JsWindow object. self and window properties refer to the window object itself. You can use these to make the current window reference. parent frames array refer to other JsWindow objects related to the current one.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

innerHeight

public static final Value.Integer.Member innerHeight

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsWindow object refers to a read-only integer value specifying the height, in pixels, of the document display area of this window. This dimension does not include the size of the menu bar, tool bars, scroll bars, and so on. The property is not supported by IE. Instead use the JsHTMLElement.clientHeight property of JsDocument.documentElement or JsHTMLDocument.body depending on the version of IE.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

Method Detail

alert

public final void alert(java.lang.Object message)

Displays a simple message in a dialog box.

In JavaScript, this method displays the specified message to the user in a dialog box. The dialog box contains an OK button the user can click to dismiss it. The dialog box is typically modal, and the call to this function typically blocks until the dialog is dismissed.

Perhaps the most common use of this method is to display error messages when the user's input to some form element is invalid in some way. The alert dialog box can inform the user of the problem and explain what needs to be corrected to avoid the problem in the future

The appearance of the dialog box is platform-dependent, but it generally contains graphics that indicate an error, warning, or alert message of some kind. While it can display any desired message, the alert graphics of the dialog box mean that this method is not appropriate for simple informational messages like "Welcome to my blog"

Note that the message displayed in the dialog box is a string of plain text, not formatted HTML. You can use the newline character "\n" in your strings to break your message across multiple lines. You can also do some rudimentary formatting using spaces and can approximate horizontal rules with underscore characters, but the results depend greatly on the font used in the dialog box and thus are system-dependent.

Parameters:
message - The plain-text (not HTML) string to display in a dialog box popped up over the current window.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
Js.alert(Object), Global.alert(Object), Global.alert(Object)
JavaScript:

confirm

public final java.lang.Boolean confirm(java.lang.Object question)

Asks a yes-or-no question with a dialog box.

In JavaScript, this method displays the specified question in a dialog box. The dialog box contains OK and Cancel buttons that the user can use to answer the question. If the user clicks the OK button, it returns true. If the user clicks Cancel, it returns false.

The dialog box that is displayed by the this method is modal. That is, it blocks all user input to the main browser window until the user dismisses the dialog box by clicking on the OK or Cancel buttons. Since this method returns a value depending on the user's response to the dialog box, JavaScript execution pauses in the call to this method, and subsequent statements are not executed until the user responds to the dialog box.

There is no way to change the labels that appear in the buttons of the dialog box (to make them read Yes and No, for example). Therefore, you should take care to phrase your question or message so that OK and Cancel are suitable responses.

Parameters:
question - The plain-text (not HTML) string to be displayed in the dialog box. It should generally express a question you want the user to answer.
Returns:
true if the user clicks the OK button; false if the user clicks the Cancel button.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
Js.confirm(Object), Global.confirm(Object), Global.confirm(Object)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

public final java.lang.String prompt(java.lang.Object message)

Asks for simple string input with a dialog box.

This method displays text input field and OK and Cancel buttons in a dialog box. Platform-dependent graphics in the dialog box help indicate to the user that an input is desired.

addEventListener

public final void addEventListener(java.lang.String type,
                                   JsFunction<?> listener,
                                   java.lang.Boolean useCapture)

Adds an event handler function to the set of event handlers for this node. This is a DOM-standard method supported by all modern browsers except IE.

This method adds the specified event listener function to the set of listeners registered on this node to handle events of the specified type. If useCapture is true, the listener is registered as a capturing event listener. If useCapture is false, it is registered as a normal event listener.

This method may be called multiple times to register multiple event handlers for the same type of event on the same node. Note, however, that the DOM Specification makes no guarantees about the order in which multiple event handlers are invoked.

If the same event listener function is registered twice on the same node with the same type and useCapture arguments, the second registration is simply ignored. If a new event listener is registered on this node while an event is being handled at this node, the new event listener is not invoked for that event.

When a node is duplicated with JsNode.cloneNode(Boolean) or JsDocument.importNode(JsNode, Boolean), the event listeners registered for the original node are not copied.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
addEventListener in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be invoked.
listener - The event listener function that is invoked when an event of the specified type is dispatched to this node. When invoked, the listener function is passed an JsEvent object and is invoked as a method of the node on which it is registered.
useCapture - If true, the specified listener is to be invoked only during the capturing phase of event propagation. The more common value of false means that the listener is not invoked during the capturing phase but instead is invoked when this node is the actual event target or when the event bubbles up to this node from its original target.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
attachEvent(String, JsFunction), removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsElement.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsDocument.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

removeEventListener

public final void removeEventListener(java.lang.String type,
                                      JsFunction<?> listener,
                                      java.lang.Boolean useCapture)

Removes an event handler function from the set of handlers for this node. This is a standard DOM method implemented by all modern browsers except IE.

This method removes the specified event listener function. The type and useCapture arguments must be the same as they are in the corresponding call to addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean). If no event listener is found that matches the specified arguments, this method does nothing.

Once an event listener function has been removed by this method, it will no longer be invoked for the specified type of event on this node. This is true even if the event listener is removed by another event listener registered for the same type of event on the same node.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsDocument objects

Specified by:
removeEventListener in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be deleted.
listener - The event listener function that is to be removed.
useCapture - true if a capturing event listener is to be removed; false if a normal event listener is to be removed.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
detachEvent(String, JsFunction), addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsElement.removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsDocument.removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean)

attachEvent

public final void attachEvent(java.lang.String type,
                              JsFunction<?> listener)

Adds an event handler function to the set of handlers for this node. This is the IE-specific alternative to addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean).

This method is an IE-specific event registration method. It serves the same purpose as the standard addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean) method, which IE does not support, but is different from that function in several important ways:

  • Since the IE event model does not support event capturing, this method and detachEvent(String, JsFunction) expect only two arguments: the event type and the handler function.
  • The event handler names passed to the IE methods should include the "on" prefix.
  • Functions registered with this method are invoked with no JsEvent event property of window object.
  • Functions registered with this method are invoked as global functions, rather than as methods of the node on which the event occurred. That is, when an event handler registered with this method executes, the this keyword refers to window object, not to the event's target node.
  • This method allows the same event handler function to be registered more than once. When an event of the specified type occurs, the registered function is invoked as many times as it is registered.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsDocument objects

Specified by:
attachEvent in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be invoked, with a leading "on" prefix.
listener - The event listener function that is invoked when an event of the specified type is dispatched to this node. This function is not passed any event property of the JsWindow object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), detachEvent(String, JsFunction), JsElement.attachEvent(String, JsFunction), JsDocument.attachEvent(String, JsFunction)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

detachEvent

public final void detachEvent(java.lang.String type,
                              JsFunction<?> listener)

Removes an event handler function from this node. This is the IE-specific alternative to the standard removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean) method.

This method undoes the event handler function registration performed by the attachEvent(String, JsFunction) method. It is the IE-specific analog to the standard removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean). To remove an event handler function for a node, simply invoke this method with the same arguments you originally passed to attachEvent(String, JsFunction).

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsDocument objects

getComputedStyle

public final JsCSS2Properties getComputedStyle(JsHTMLElement elt)

Determines the CSS styles that apply to a document element.

An element in a document may obtain style information from an inline style attribute and from any number of style sheets in the stylesheet "cascade." Before the element can actually be displayed in a view, its style information must be extracted from the cascade, and styles specified with relative units (such as percentages or "ems") must be "computed" to convert to absolute units.

This method returns a read-only CSS2Properties object that represents those cascaded and computed styles. The DOM specification requires that any styles representing lengths use absolute units such as inches or millimeters. In practice, pixel values are commonly returned instead, although there is no guarantee that an implementation will always do this.

Contrast this method with the style property of an HTMLElement, which gives you access only to the inline styles of an element, in whatever units they were specified, and tells you nothing about stylesheet styles that apply to the element.

In Internet Explorer, similar functionality is available through the nonstandard currentStyle property of each HTMLElement object.

Parameters:
elt - The document element whose style information is desired.
Returns:
A read-only CSS2Properties object that represents the style attributes and values used to render the specified element in this window. Any length values queried from this object are always expressed as pixel or absolute values, not relative or percentage values.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

blur

public void blur()

Takes keyboard focus away from the top-level browser window.

This method removes keyboard focus from the top-level browser window specified by the current JsWindow object. It is unspecified which window gains keyboard focus as a result. In some browsers and/or platforms, this method may have no effect.

close

public void close()

Closes the window.

This method method closes the top-level browser window specified by the current JsWindow object. A window can close itself by calling this method on itself or self. Only windows opened by JavaScript can be closed by JavaScript. This prevents malicious scripts from causing the user's browser to exit.

Since:
1.0
See Also:

focus

public void focus()

Gives the top-level browser window keyboard focus and brings the window to the front on most platforms.

This method gives keyboard focus to the browser window specified by the current JsWindow object.

On most platforms, a top-level window is brought forward to the top of the window stack so that it becomes visible when it is given focus.

moveBy

public void moveBy(java.lang.Integer dx,
                   java.lang.Integer dy)

Moves the window by a relative amount.

This method moves the window to the relative position specified by dx and dy. For security resasons, browsers may restrict this method so it cannot move a window offscreen. It is usually a bad idea to move a user's browser window unless he explicitly request it. Scripts should typically use this method only on windows that they created themselves with the open(String, String, String, Boolean) method.

Parameters:
dx - The number of pixels to move the window to the right.
dy - The number of pixels to move the window down.
Since:
1.0

resizeBy

public void resizeBy(java.lang.Integer dw,
                     java.lang.Integer dh)

Resizes the window by a specified amount.

This method resizes the window by the relative amounts specified by dw and dh. For security reasons, the browser may restrict this method to prevent scripts from making windows very small. For usability reasons, it is almost always a bad idea to change the size of a user's window. If a script created a window, the script can resize it, but it is bad form for a script to resize the window that it is loaded into.

Parameters:
dw - The number of pixels by which to increase the width of the window.
dh - The number of pixels by which to increase the height of the window.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
